commit_message:
Add experimental glusterfs centos7 job

We have found a number of issues with centos7 since we started

 - issues with increased memory size [1]
 - missing updates [2]
 - swap configuration [3]

I believe we should have no issues running the glusterfs jobs on
centos as we were doing originally.  Add an experiemental test to do
some testing.

[1] https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/oom-in-rax-centos7-CI-job
[2] I0eb7119b03dbbfe6697a656dfe57186f9a1ef791
[3] I09974be88cc590cf9ffbd16db58c19131c9532aa

Change-Id: I9f7a7dee8c08568c9c53f942642777f1fe8200f1

commit_message:
Disable all python34 jobs for stable/icehouse

python34 interpreter is not installed on images that are used for
Icehouse. So there is no way any of those jobs will succeed for the
branch.

Disable them all instead of doing it per-project.

Change-Id: I146e0bd2d80b22a1270790e8c381212e36528e56

commit_message:
Ensure we run the full tempest job serially without admin

This commit fixes a previous oversight to the non-admin tempest job
definition. Previously the job was configured to run the smoke tagged
subset of tempest in parallel. However we need to run the full suite
serially with the non-admin job. This adds the missing flag to the
definition.

Change-Id: Ie54d282d222b79dcc36fd3087665888f5094bf36

commit_message:
Allow name or ID for update_subnet()

Even though the subnet name is an updatable value, we should still
allow specifying the name of the subnet to update along with the ID.
This implies that we need to error if a name is used and multiple
matches are found, since name is not a unique attribute.

Change-Id: Ie57900a3a31f470c5e411e0c9c141ede8b95e0b2

commit_message:
Allow name or ID for update_router()

Even though the router name is an updatable value, we should still
allow specifying the name of the router to update along with the ID.
This implies that we need to error if a name is used and multiple
matches are found, since name is not a unique attribute.

Change-Id: I17535ad363f0ff19fdc0fdde9fa472c7ce263b23

commit_message:
[install-guide] install additional glance packages

It is necessary to install openstack-glance (includes glance-manage) and
python-glance.

The manual installation of python-glance is a workaround for
https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1213545.

Partially implements bp installguide-kilo.

Change-Id: I90e7eca0b4ae709e0e412e4c8ed866c57e480c0f

commit_message:
Fix for l2-gateway-connection-delete error

The patch set fixes the problem described in launchpad
bug 1445770 where l2-gateway-connection-delete reports
an error when there are VMs on the network associated
with the connection.

Closes-Bug: 1445770

Change-Id: I76278bda7bfbd3cc997166ca13f985878e06a5cd

IMHO we really should never be calling this without the data Nova knows. Actually we should probably never be trying to parse the libvirt xml to figure out what disks belong to the instance. All of this should be known by Nova already.

Also disk_available_least that we report makes little sense for a number of libvirt image backends (like for example rbd), and is not used anywhere other than the fact that we return it from the API.

This patch aims to fix the fact that nova compute may fail to start if iscsi targets are down (a pretty abd bug) for Kilo.

commit_message:
libvirt: make _get_instance_disk_info conservative

We want to make sure we never try to get the size of an attached volume
when doing _get_instance_disk_info (as this can cause issues when
gathering available resources).

libvirt's get_available_resources will call upon it to determine the
available disk size on the compute node, but do so without providing
information about block devices. This makes _get_instance_disk_info make
incorrect guesses as to which device is a volume

This patch makes the _get_instance_disk_info be more conservative about
it's guesses when it can not reasonably determine if a device is a
volume or not.

Change-Id: Ifb20655c32896b640672917e3840add81b136780
Partial-bug: #1445021
Partial-Bug: #1371677

commit_message:
Add a PgSQL Designate DSVM Job

PostgreSQL support in Designate has been very hit and miss
due to not having a gate ensuring all reviews are functional
against PgSQL. We add a new experimental gate for only the
PowerDNS backend, as it will exercise both the Designate
and PowerDNS database inteactions.

Change-Id: I09229b3db19c92e7af138c00eec67197e640558d

commit_message:
Remove extra tarball lines

The publish-to-pypi template already contains tarball jobs for release
and pre-release. Thus they are not needed in individual projects, remove
them where they exist.

The python-jobs template already includes a -branch-tarball job for
post, remove it from jobs that use the python-jobs template.

Change-Id: I368e5bafe747c130c97f9b6855dee43b322d28e6

commit_message:
[install-guide] [yum] rename MongoDB config file to /etc/mongod.conf

The configuration file changed from /etc/mongodb.conf to
/etc/mongod.conf with MongoDB version 2.6.7.

https://lists.fedoraproject.org/pipermail/devel/2015-January/207346.html

Partially implements bp installguide-kilo.

commit_message:
Enable flavor retrieval by name

This patch adds a method for flavor to be retrieved by name. The default
Resource.get() method is not suitable for this case, while referencing
flavors by name is much easier/portable than referencing them by IDs.

Change-Id: I0e88bbb3a3a832b866169e648f3ca07dd42e2a27

commit_message:
Revised cluster action for node user/proj properties

For cluster create and cluster scale-out actions, we have the nodes
inherit the user/project/domain propoerties from the cluster.

Change-Id: I725d0ca810fb7dd4a23e07ade438653c6909db1d

[{'created': '2015-04-01 14:44:18.000000000', 'message': 'Better power_state logging in _sync_instance_power_state

Commit aa1792eb4c1d10e9a192142ce7e20d37871d916a added more verbose
logging of the various database and hypervisor states when
_sync_instance_power_state is called (which can be called from
handle_lifecycle_event - triggered by the libvirt driver, or from the
_sync_power_states periodic task).

This change adds logging of when the power_state in the database does
not match the power_state from the hypervisor, and then the power_state
in the database is updated to match what's in the hypervisor.

Also, we save the original database power_state for logging when we have
cases of stopping an active instance due to vm_state / power_state
conflicts, or stopping a "stopped" instance but the hypervisor says is
still running.

This is all needed because debugging the various things that can hit
this code at different times and cause problems is, well, terrible.

Conflicts:
        nova/compute/manager.py

NOTE(mriedem): The conflict is due to commit 1e8df2f00 on master
which changed LOG.warn to LOG.warning.

Closes-Bug: #1439223

Change-Id: I297ca0037f43535c80afa8a4b5086ccb30558dc3
(cherry picked from commit 26424b883e3cbd4c1abc1738b417eb6823b0e3cd)
'}]
commit_message:
Better power_state logging in _sync_instance_power_state

Commit aa1792eb4c1d10e9a192142ce7e20d37871d916a added more verbose
logging of the various database and hypervisor states when
_sync_instance_power_state is called (which can be called from
handle_lifecycle_event - triggered by the libvirt driver, or from the
_sync_power_states periodic task).

This change adds logging of when the power_state in the database does
not match the power_state from the hypervisor, and then the power_state
in the database is updated to match what's in the hypervisor.

Also, we save the original database power_state for logging when we have
cases of stopping an active instance due to vm_state / power_state
conflicts, or stopping a "stopped" instance but the hypervisor says is
still running.

This is all needed because debugging the various things that can hit
this code at different times and cause problems is, well, terrible.

Conflicts:
        nova/compute/manager.py

NOTE(mriedem): The conflict is due to commit 1e8df2f00 on master
which changed LOG.warn to LOG.warning.

Closes-Bug: #1439223

Change-Id: I297ca0037f43535c80afa8a4b5086ccb30558dc3
(cherry picked from commit 26424b883e3cbd4c1abc1738b417eb6823b0e3cd)

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-02 06:30:20.000000000', 'message': "Add a simple memory/process tracking service

We are experiencing OOM issues with centos/cinder jobs which are
turning out to be quite difficult to replicate anywhere but in the
gate on rax hosts.

Although we currently have 'dstat' running through the run, this
doesn't always give you the whole view.  It doesn't show important
things like what vm's have started up, or what processes might be
hanging around stuck in various states.

Logging this data isn't appropriate for every job, but it would be
really nice to be able to get much better insight into such an issue
like this by simply turning on a service.  It would avoid nodepool
root-users needing to be around to do this sort of poking on
everyone's behalf by logging into hosts.

This adds a memtracker service which collects /proc data, ps data
including memory usage, number of threads, wait-channel, cpu-time and
command-line in a tight loop.

Also added is a very simple analysis script

Change-Id: Id622a818e3d98eabf014971f46ed66a6a63b64bb

commit_message:
Add a simple memory/process tracking service

We are experiencing OOM issues with centos/cinder jobs which are
turning out to be quite difficult to replicate anywhere but in the
gate on rax hosts.

Although we currently have 'dstat' running through the run, this
doesn't always give you the whole view.  It doesn't show important
things like what vm's have started up, or what processes might be
hanging around stuck in various states.

Logging this data isn't appropriate for every job, but it would be
really nice to be able to get much better insight into such an issue
like this by simply turning on a service.  It would avoid nodepool
root-users needing to be around to do this sort of poking on
everyone's behalf by logging into hosts.

This adds a memtracker service which collects /proc data, ps data
including memory usage, number of threads, wait-channel, cpu-time and
command-line in a tight loop.

Also added is a very simple analysis script

Change-Id: Id622a818e3d98eabf014971f46ed66a6a63b64bb

(2 comments)

Try to keep non-related style-only changes out of patches, just FYI.

I personally don't feel this makes the code all that much more readable. It's still ugly as all get-out. Instead of calling actual object methods, it's still doing the silly session._call_method(vutil, 'cancel_retrieval') crap that makes me cringe. Would be so much nicer to see code that did stuff like:

 vutil.cancel_retrieval(session, results)

or even:

 session.cancel_retrieval(results)

(and have the session object hide all the vutil module accesses...)

Anyway, I've verified in the oslo_vmware lib that this code is technically correct (as far as the string renames from things like 'cancel_retrieve' to 'cancel_retrieval', so I'll give this just a +1 because it's hard for me to stomach a +2 on this refactoring ;)

commit_message:
VMware: use oslo.vmware methods for handling tokens

When the VC has paginated results it returns a token. We now
make use of utilities provided by oslo.vmware to continue the
retrieval of the tokens or to cancel the retrieval of the
tokens.

This makes use of methods provided by oslo.vmware. It is far
cleaner and robust than the previous code.

Change-Id: I389496418d9b97a32561c5c2183ea549bfa908b2

[{'created': '2015-01-28 15:30:47.000000000', 'message': "Remove use of setuptools internals for scripts

Before we were hooking in to setuptools internals in order to override
the text of the script we want to write. Due to a refactoring in
setuptools, some of those things were even more private/hidden - but it
turns out that now we've got a place we can easily override to do what
we want.

Change-Id: I626909b320ad0b14f95022fe3416dddff8f68f79
"}, {'created': '2015-01-28 15:45:16.000000000', 'message': "Remove use of setuptools internals for scripts

Before we were hooking in to setuptools internals in order to override
the text of the script we want to write. Due to a refactoring in
setuptools, some of those things were even more private/hidden - but it
turns out that now we've got a place we can easily override to do what
we want.

On old setuptools - keep doing what we were doing back then.

Change-Id: I626909b320ad0b14f95022fe3416dddff8f68f79
"}]
commit_message:
Remove use of setuptools internals for scripts

Before we were hooking in to setuptools internals in order to override
the text of the script we want to write. Due to a refactoring in
setuptools, some of those things were even more private/hidden - but it
turns out that now we've got a place we can easily override to do what
we want.

On old setuptools - keep doing what we were doing back then.

Change-Id: I626909b320ad0b14f95022fe3416dddff8f68f79

commit_message:
Add scope prefix in configuring host aggregates

Using unscoped key pairs will cause conflicts between
ComputeCapabilitiesFilter and AggregateInstanceExtraSpecsFilter.
And that conflicts lead to return 0 hosts of
ComputeCapabilitiesFilter.

This patch adds 'aggregate_instance_extra_specs' scope when
configuring host aggregates to avoid above conflicts.

Closes-Bug: #1445285

Change-Id: I4af09b1a556f5f9c56fb4e6fb3098fc01fb386bf

commit_message:
Consume script-writer flag in modern setuptools

A patch has been submitted to setuptools that allows for clean
overriding of the ScriptWriter class. This will detect that patch's
existence and will use it if it's there. It degrades cleanly and should
be safe to land before the setuptools patch - but we should wait anyway.

Change-Id: Ia85b6ed08396b9fc3363726fb5773759357e46fc

commit_message:
Update change password extension

Also, correct other admin action extensions - the path was wrong,
the code samples were not up-to-date, and the language
in the main chapter file was inconsistent.
Corrected all those issues.

Getting the cells Tempest job to green has been a long process because
there have been constant regressions to keep up with.  In order to get
ahead of that the final failing tests have been blacklisted and
annotated with open bugs for them.  Work will continue to address them.

Change-Id: Iffccba724c3c45b33a134355fc681e3497b84b3a
'}]
commit_message:
Blacklist last failing Tempest tests for cells job

Getting the cells Tempest job to green has been a long process because
there have been constant regressions to keep up with.  In order to get
ahead of that the final failing tests have been blacklisted and
annotated with open bugs for them.  Work will continue to address them.

Change-Id: Iffccba724c3c45b33a134355fc681e3497b84b3a

commit_message:
Open MKFS_OPTS for extension in disk-image-create

At present, MKFS_OPTS is closed for modification. The ability
to extend the set of MKFS_OPTS adds a great deal of power for
knowledgeable end-users. (And in some specific circumstances,
it is vital to success, as in the case of building RHEL/CentOS
6 images from RHEL/CentOS 7 hosts, in which case -O ^64bit is
required in order for the image to boot.)

Change-Id: I714e86a5a413779e63f598fbbb5a79d23cf6d8c3

[{'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-01-13 21:29:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-01-13 21:35:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

My previous change https://review.openstack.org/#/c/141206/ modified oslo_concurrency to have a reliable behaviour in all cases (Python 2 or Python 3, ascii or non-ascii output).

I don't like this new change because it reintroduces the different type depending on the output (ascii or non-ascii). I proposed the change because Doug Hellman complained that I changed the API (execute() now returns unicode instead of bytes on Python 2).

If we want to hide passwords in all cases and support non-ascii ouptut, IMO we should modify mask_password() to support bytes (return bytes if the input is bytes):
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/137600/"}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-01-13 21:37:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Another option is to add a new option or a new function which would always return bytes (on Python 2 and Python 3) and don't process output (don't hide passwords, even on error)."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-01-13 23:41:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

This change is my second try to port processutils to Python 3.

My first try was to always use Unicode on Python 2 *and* Python 3:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/141206/

But this change broke nova which uses execute() to get a binary output from openssl:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/oslo.concurrency/+bug/1410348

IMO we should modify execute() and ssh_execute() to support requesting to always get bytes, on Python 2 and Python 3. It means that mask_password() should also support this, don't try to decode the input, probably with a new optional parameter.

I will try to implement this, but first I would prefer to see this change merged. Doug Hellmann indirectly proposed to use encoding=None to request bytes, so it doesn't change the API proposed in this changeset."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-01-16 10:11:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

> I think user won't expect results of execute() and ssh_execute() change when locale settings change. I think we should explicitly use UTF-8 and 'surrogateescape' instead of relying on 'filesystem' encoding.

I worked on CPython to fix Unicode issues mostly between Python 3.0 and 3.3 (and some minor remaining issues in 3.4 and 3.5). I fixes issues on many platforms (Windows, Linux, Mac OS X, Solaris, FreeBSD, etc.). Not only the locale encoding is the best choice, but it's also the only choice when you need to communicate with the OS and with other applications. The locale encoding is used for many OS data: command line arguments, environment variables, filenames, many functions in the Python os module, even some in the socket module, etc.

To be exact, my patch uses sys.getfilesystemencoding() which is the locale encoding read at Python startup, so a Python process will always use the same encoding (to avoid mojibake), a requirement to ensure that os.fsencode(os.fsdecode(x)) == x.

If you decode a stdout/stderr from an encoding different than the locale encoding (let's say that we use UTF-8), you will get unicode encode errors when you reuse read data to write it into a file (open() uses the locale encoding too by default), to write it on a comand line (ditto), or anything else that uses the locale encoding.

If you still consider that you always control the encoding is all places of your application (ex: the encoding is *always* forced to UTF-8), we can reconsider the reintroduction of the optional encoding parameter.

For your information, the subprocess.Popen has *no* encoding parameter. It returns bytes by default, or Unicode decoded from the locale encoding when universal_newlines=True is used."}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-04-18 08:56:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

For further readings, I wrote a free ebook on Programming with Unicode. Here is the section on Python:
https://unicodebook.readthedocs.org/programming_languages.html#python

Here is a very short summary of Python3:
https://haypo-notes.readthedocs.org/unicode.html#python-3'}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2015-04-18 10:20:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: Code-Review+2

Yeah, that's pretty much the thought I had this morning: all commands and SSH should agree to use to use and pass locale encoding. And from what I see in docs and configs, it is currently the case. Thanks for detailed explanation though!"}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-04-18 13:01:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

> Yeah, that's pretty much the thought I had this morning: all commands and SSH should agree to use to use and pass locale encoding. And from what I see in docs and configs, it is currently the case. Thanks for detailed explanation though!

OpenStack applications will be slowly ported to Python 3 during Liberty cycle. If we find real use cases where it's important to specify the encoding on execute/ssh_execute, we can later add again the encoding (and also maybe encoding_errors) parameter(s). But my patch is only a first step to Python 3."}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-04-18 23:22:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

always Unicode (instead of bytes). The ProcessExecutionError is raised
by execute() on error.

commit_message:
Port processutils to Python 3

On Python 3, execute() and ssh_execute() now return stdout and stderr as
Unicode. os.fsdecode() is used to stdout and stderr, it uses the locale
encoding with the surrogateescape error handler.
subprocess.Popen(universal_encoding=True) uses the same encoding and
error handler.

This change breaks the backward compatibility, but I believe that
Unicode is more convinient in Python 3 and it is what users expect. In
practice, there is no known (OpenStack) application compatible with
Python 3 using oslo_concurrency.processutils yet.

Add new tests.

This changeset does not change the behaviour on Python 2, only Python 3
is impacted.

Change-Id: Ibb510642c1440e2fbe7ad53d797bc7c32a3cbddf

commit_message:
Enable ceilometer service on Heat gates

Previously most part of services was disabled to safe time.
In this patch we enable ceilometer resource, due to it's alarm system by
default. As example test https://review.openstack.org/#/c/153192/
fails due to error in AWS LB which uses Alarm resource.

Change-Id: Ief9470fd74ad1f3bcb696a3eb58d840a8db099c3

commit_message:
networking-ovn: enable mysql and rabbitmq

The devstack job for the networking-ovn repo overrides the list of
enabled services to be a minimal set.  Unfortunately, it's missing
mysql and rabbitmq which are required for devstack to start up
successfully with the other services that are enabled.

This patch also fixes enabling keystone by specifying it as 'key'
instead of 'keystone'.

Change-Id: I29a3b2c03559aeaba7c08431bfbed1fe21762666

commit_message:
Migrate ssh.py from tempest

This commit migrates the ssh common module from tempest. This module
provides a wrapper around paramiko to provide ssh connectivity to
a remote server for testing.

At the time of this migration commit the latest Change-Id for
the module was:

 * tempest/common/ssh.py: Ia0de957b681cb924a57af98d99a9389ee234ed5b

Change-Id: Iad5ffbfe18690f1b6f178dde31a8ec0d0666c815

commit_message:
Switch default Fedora image to F21

Fedora 21 was release 4 months ago, we should switch to use it as default
before it goes EOL.

Change-Id: I72686911cc21aeb75d61430878dd36c54edb6904

commit_message:
Use TLS container UUIDs in Radware LBaaS

Pass TLS container UUIDs to the Radware LBaaS backend
for using it as an internak entity identifier

Update developer doc to reference Ubuntu 14

commit_message:
Move common checks into base testcase

The assertion for logging being correct and not using deprecated
function needs to apply to every test to be effective, so add
it to the base testcase class.

Change-Id: I19e208c5e11fdc5227a1250782b13bf82dfdd699

commit_message:
Apply a naming rule of GET to messaging client

[GET /resources] methods should be "list_<resource name>s"
or "show_<resource name>", so this patch applies the rule
to messaging client.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: Ibae5f78b3dee12dbab5095872b8d868fbfec7f5d

Adding port_admin_state_change option to config

Adding the ability to skip test_update_instance_port_admin_state
when this operation is not supported by the test environment.
Closes-Bug: 1436839

Change-Id: Icda251c46e2fefcc80b0c712d6f42d76a7d247b7

commit_message:
cinder list now supports filter by tenant

Admin can now filter volumes on the basis of tenant.
Also updated help argument, to be consistent over the
v1 and v2 shell module.

Closes-Bug: #1341411
Change-Id: I647f0c9331ee4cd27acbfada6cdb9a56f80701b4

[{'created': '2015-04-17 10:46:09.000000000', 'message': "Set loading strategy to joined for Routerport/Port

The RouterPort model has a relationship to the ports model which
is frequently relied on to get the port IDs of interfaces attached
to a router. However, this defaults to the loading strategy to
'select', which meant a new query was being emitted for every
interface to the ports table just to get the ID.

This patch adjusts the relationship to be 'joined' by default so
one query will fetch the related ports.

Another option would have been not to use the port object at all since
the ID is all that the callers were usually interested in. However,
they would end up using the ID to do a port lookup, which is being
optimized away in another patch anyway so the full port object from
the relationship will end up getting used.

commit_message:
Set loading strategy to joined for Routerport/Port

The RouterPort model has a relationship to the ports model which
is frequently relied on to get the port IDs of interfaces attached
to a router. However, this defaults to the loading strategy to
'select', which meant a new query was being emitted for every
interface to the ports table just to get the ID.

This patch adjusts the relationship to be 'joined' by default so
one query will fetch the related ports.

Another option would have been not to use the port object at all since
the ID is all that the callers were usually interested in. However,
they would end up using the ID to do a port lookup, which is being
optimized away in another patch anyway so the full port object from
the relationship will end up getting used.

Change-Id: Id1ae35f845f7367d5f1f065c6fa637da7b980a2b
Partial-Bug: #1445412

commit_message:
Enable version discovery

The service catalog can now have the cinder endpoint x.x.x.x:8776 with
service_type volume, without needing to specify a version in the
endpoint. Keystone will do discovery of the root / GET of the Cinder API
to discover the versions that can be talked to.

This also provides backwards compatibility for the previous solution of
having v1 enabled on service_type volume and v2 on service_type
volumev2.

Change-Id: Id0347f8370dbc8fd7fa8096cd5859e10b0c5d67c

commit_message:
Fix test accounts unit test race with networks

Previously the unit tests for the accounts providers were assuming that
all tests would be run in order. This was causing an occasional failure
when 1 of 2 accounts with a network in the fake accounts list were used
for a test not mocking the network clients. This commit addresses this
issue by changing the fake test list in setUp to not use accounts with
networks. Then the test which does test accounts with networks will do
a cleanup on the mock from setup and use it's own accounts list.

Closes-Bug: #1446309

Change-Id: Id7eedc4f9063f33287c945ed72edd59f52d80952

commit_message:
removing unused module cue.common.utils

cue.common.utils is mostly unused by cue other than a safe_rstrip
function used by the API auth middleware.  Modified auth middleware to
no longer depend on cue.common.utils and removed cue.common.utils

Change-Id: I457a8d2b214bebd54a6430eda3eb9351226b9a37

Extend PCI Passthrough Whitelist to support range for doamin,
bus,slot and function fields in the address.
This way a user will be able to exclude VF(s) which are used
for other purposes.

syntax example:
pci_passthrough_whitelist={"address":"*:02:00.2-*","physical_network":"physnet1"}
this will syntax will allow to allocate VF which their fucntions are from 2 til max

pci_passthrough_whitelist={"address":"*:02:1-2.*","physical_network":"physnet1"}
this will syntax will allow to allocate VF which their slot are between 1 to 2

commit_message:
Add range support to all address fields in pci_passthrough_whitelist

Extend PCI Passthrough Whitelist to support range for domain,
bus, slot and function fields in the address.
This way a user will be able to exclude VF(s) which are used
for other purposes.

For example:
pci_passthrough_whitelist={"address":"*:02:00.2-","physical_network":"physnet1"}

This allows allocation of VFs whose functions are from 2 upwards.

pci_passthrough_whitelist={"address":"*:02:00.-2","physical_network":"physnet1"}

This allows allocation of VFs whose functions are from 2 downwards.

pci_passthrough_whitelist={"address":"*:02:1-2.*","physical_network":"physnet1"}

This allows allocation of VFs whose slots are between 1 and 2.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1407721

Change-Id: I24de9cfb6f94f25fbdb115f1aafeed606899e919

commit_message:
Remove tox working folder when recloning

After recloning, devstack deletes all the pyc files from
the cloned repositories.  Runing tox will also generate
.tox folder which needs to be removed as well.

Change-Id: I3ac6508789f99e7ac63cc7b97a1e4d2e997e4080

commit_message:
Replace custom method call logger with oslo.log helper

oslo.log now provides a logging helper that is similar to custom neutron
helper (actually, the helper in oslo.log started from neutron version).

Now switching to library implementation.

Deprecated neutron.common.log.log

commit_message:
Hyper-V: checks for existent Notes in list_instance_notes

If there are VMs with Notes = None, the Hyper-V Driver cannot
start, as it tries to iterate over None, which results in an
exception.

This commit adds a check if the Notes exist, before iterating over
them.

Closes-Bug: #1438638

Change-Id: Icebdc03d7249fdf903b94b2f61f4891f5c9d6e50

commit_message:
ml2_conf.ini OVS values were missing

On ubuntu, the openvswitch template is rendered into the ml2
template. Some of openvswitch template variables were missing
from the ml2 template definition.

Change-Id: I62274d2a1c15e6d7e2a5079b0182513ee18f67b2
Closes-Bug: #1444647

commit_message:
Configure "reserved_host_memory_mb" attribute to support bare metal

The "reserved_host_memory_mb" attribute is default to 512MB when not
setting, it will make flavor match failed, so for bare metal service,
we need to set it to "0", no need to reserve host memory.

Change-Id: Idce5e5c223fdcbd59ae9304819ae04b1de8c1c3c
Closes-bug: #1446035

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-09 04:10:06.000000000', 'message': 'Add a peak memory tracker to dstat

We can see memory usage during the run with dstat but we have no
insight into what is consuming the memory.

This adds a tracker to dstat that records a snapshot of peak memory
usage during a run.

The intent is to add logic into the verify-pipeline jobs to use this
report and send statistics on peak memory usage to statsd [1].  We can
then build a picture of memory-usage growth over time.  This should
allow better insight into an issues such as that introduced by
Idf3a3a914b54779172776822710b3e52e751b1d1 where memory-usage jumped

commit_message:
Add a peak memory tracker to dstat

We can see at-a-glance memory usage during the run with dstat but we
have no way to break that down into an overview of where memory is
going.

This adds a peer-service to dstat that records snapshots of the system
during peak memory usage.  It checks periodically if there is less
memory available than before and, if so, records the running processes
and vm overview.

The intent is to add logic into the verify-pipeline jobs to use this
report and send statistics on peak memory usage to statsd [1].  We can
then build a picture of memory-usage growth over time.  This type of
report would have allowed better insight into issues such as
introduced by Idf3a3a914b54779172776822710b3e52e751b1d1 where
memory-usage jumped dramatically after switching to pip versions of
libraries.  Tracking details of memory usage is going to be an
important part of future development.

[1] http://graphite.openstack.org/

Change-Id: I4b0a8f382dcaa09331987ab84a68546ec29cbc18

commit_message:
Avoid double-hopping deletes for security group rules

There is no need to get and delete; we can delete with one bullet.
This will most likely have quite a decent performance benefit overall.

The patch preserves the existing logic of raising and error on the missing
element; a test was added to spur up the coverage.

Related-bug: #1444112

Change-Id: Iaef77bd3f7775ed91d374838fb5488d925b4062c

commit_message:
Clarify the init logic for the ML2 plugin

This patch cleans up the init logic for the plugin so that
we better separate the tasks required for establishing
the integration with DHCP and RPC layers.

In other words: some bikeshedding whilst dealing with bug #1444112

Change-Id: I68710ad002b0e1b5bff40baa5de343b0bd7ecea6

commit_message:
Fix unnecessary dotted focus outline in tab bar

In Firefox, the tab bar in "Volumes" and "System Information" pages 
displays unnecessary dotted focus outline.  This is not the case with
other browsers like Chrome or Safari.  This is fixed by adding
'outline:none' to :focus in the tab bar styling (there is already CSS
for :focus).

Change-Id: I3f7065003d3c0ec20fa1d3f0189e208bb36e9b94
Closes-Bug: 1431341

commit_message:
WebSSO should use remote_id_attribute by protocol

WebSSO always use the remote_id_attribute from the
[federation] group. Fix the issue, by consuming the
protocol specific remote_id_attribute if available.

Change-Id: Icdc693965ec53e5ff8f1901af26c9232a20aef7e
Closes-Bug: #1441827
(cherry picked from commit 9b11d13856034e3a2cf6ab1f6ca80a6965818d17)

commit_message:
backend_argument should be marked secret

Since the backend_argument can potentially contain a password,
it should be marked secret to avoid leakage into the logs.

Closes-Bug: #1443598

Change-Id: I55663db4cf2df84a66de8f64fba4b4f129ae827d
(cherry picked from commit f9db1a65bd4d83d12c572ba4d5807845996ef410)

commit_message:
neutron: reduce complexity of allocate_for_instance (requested_networks)

We've hit the point that people can't fix bugs in the
allocate_for_instance method due to the level of complexity of the code.

This change starts refactoring the method into smaller units so it's
easier to read, easier to maintain, and more testable as small units and
reduces the overall complexity so new changes can be made.

We start by pulling out the big loop at the beginning that's processing
the list of NetworkRequest objects.

I've added inline code comments to help make the code more
understandable for what it's doing along with spacing it out a bit so
it's easier to read.

Change-Id: Ifed768070ae41a7991a3a0bfa8b63d18307c672d

inheritance  chain so super() call is unusable.

commit_message:
Make memcache client reusable across threads

memcache.Client is inherited from threading._local so instances are only
accessible from current thread or eventlet. Present workaround broke
inheritance  chain so super() call is unusable.

This patch makes artificial client class mimic inheritance from
threading._local while using generic object methods allowing reusability.

Change-Id: Ic5d5709695877afb995fd816bb0e4ce711b99b60
Closes-Bug: #1440493
(cherry picked from commit 33a95575fc3778bf8ef054f7b9d24fcb7c75100b)

commit_message:
backend_argument should be marked secret

Since the backend_argument can potentially contain a password,
it should be marked secret to avoid leakage into the logs.

Closes-Bug: #1443598

Change-Id: I55663db4cf2df84a66de8f64fba4b4f129ae827d
(cherry picked from commit f9db1a65bd4d83d12c572ba4d5807845996ef410)

commit_message:
Revert heat's keystone_authtoken configuration

Commit 6db42a6 updated heat's keystone auth middleware to support
keystone v3, however heat fails to operate with this configuration in
place.  This commit reverts this particular part of commit 6db42a6 to
to restore heat functionality.

Additionally, heat requires auth_uri to contain /v2.0, which is a
non-standard as far as the other projects are concerned.

Change-Id: I52c995e801660e21479a843b4e5410b7e3d349e1
Closes-Bug: #1445402

commit_message:
Recap keystoneclient for stable/icehouse

keystoneclient's stable/icehouse branch has 0.11.2, and since the
requirement was <=0.11.2 we can't create patches since they get
a version like 0.11.2.post1.

The release of keystoneclient after 0.11.2 was actually 1.0.0.

Change-Id: I6c08751fe0e1e0edea617d8b264a1bb6b229e655

commit_message:
Revert heat's keystone_authtoken configuration

Commit 6db42a6 updated heat's keystone auth middleware to support
keystone v3, however heat fails to operate with this configuration in
place.  This commit reverts this particular part of commit 6db42a6 to
to restore heat functionality.

Additionally, heat requires auth_uri to contain /v2.0, which is a
non-standard as far as the other projects are concerned.

Change-Id: I52c995e801660e21479a843b4e5410b7e3d349e1
Closes-Bug: #1445402
(cherry picked from commit deaf440546d3396679dc63595202a859c415b54b)

commit_message:
Mask password in logs

The logs are printing in clear all the password configured by an
admin in datasource.conf. They should be masked like nova etc.
Also change .gitreview with the right project.

Change-Id: I69764b341a4114d8c51f68e7f2a7546a15ea0822
Closes-bug: 1393123

Use a fixture and the mocking functions provided in oslo.utils.timeutils
rather than mocking the function directly. This broke when the functions
moved.

Change-Id: I65b6ae58c6b4e02e235f992c21502aa377992985
Closes-Bug: #1408838
(cherry picked from commit a4a46764491aa36ec4440c91c435578e178f14f8)

commit_message:
Remove stable-compat-jobs from python-novaclient

Since novaclient has been capped on the stable branches, there
is no use in running the stable-compat-jobs on changes proposed
to the python-novaclient master branch. These jobs should instead
be run on python-novaclient stable branches, after they are cut.

Change-Id: I7bb60e4a1906d1a903dadf94dbe4aee2af06bb0b

The drawback comapred to what you have is that the serice configuration is handled by d-g and the Jenkins job templates so local use is different.

I would suggest here that you break out the local.conf into its own file and copy it into place for local runs.  In the gate you may be able to do that with a gate hook, but now we're treading on the edge of my gate testing knowledge.

I think it is fine to have this test do a DevStack checkout and configure it, but that'll be local only unless you build totally custom gate jobs. commit_message:
Add functional test starting point

This works as near as I know.  When I start adding functional
tests, it will probably need some fine tuning, but I think this
is very close.  I also wanted to get this out there for discussion
on the approach.  I wanted to have a consistent way for all of
us to fire up a functional test environment.  This will have to
be tested in other clouds, but it should be pretty close.

Change-Id: Ibe6c3d4a155967f59e248940b2fb6a9ef8c29583

commit_message:
Sort head and body before computing a Rule's hash

The policy engine may change the order of a Rule's body before inserting the
Rule into the policy engine.  The previous version computes the Rule's hash
based on the unsorted body, so if the body order changes before the Rule
computes the hash then a subsequent attempt to remove the same Rule will fail
because the hashes do not match.

This change sorts the head and body before computing the hash so that the hash
will stay the same even if the body order changes.

Also add a test that inserts and removes a rule, and checks that the rule is
no longer in the policy engine.

Change-Id: I0f46ee22dcf3a5facff279266e927fb1290a014e

commit_message:
Adds rsyslog-install.yml in to the gate scripts.

The rsyslog-install.yml play was not being run within run-playbooks.sh
script. The change makes it so that the AIO will now have the ability
to test the rsyslog server roles.

Change-Id: I30ea36ad4fb6696aeedf76351e18e09cf5e50a1e
Closes-Bug: 1446275
(cherry picked from commit eccc83bff8895b1efbeb0ec5dc426abdd2f6e434)

commit_message:
Pull echo service out of auth_token.

Move Keystonemiddleware's Echo service out of keystonemiddleware.auth_token and
into its own module.

Change-Id: I9e557582e8361d6c2aa6e73a357b0d6c9c88ea4e
Closes-Bug: 1433251

commit_message:
Brick: Fix race in removing iSCSI device

Some folks are seeing race conditions on overloaded
or slow machines, where the time between issuing the
remove volume command, and the volume being from
/dev/disk/by-path by the kernel isn't long enough.

This patch adds the Cinder retry decorator mechanism.
This patch uses the new retry decorator to try 3 times
to wait for the volume to disappear from the system,
before moving on.

Change-Id: I24cc18d188b8eeb3b7a1392b2bd8b520dc2a0e03
Closes-Bug: 1437441

commit_message:
tests: introduce a NUMAServersTest class

Introducing a new NUMAServersTest class and two functional tests
to validate a correct creation of instances with a requested NUMA
topology, as well as to validate that instance won't be created
when the requested topology can not be satisfied.

Also, adding a method automatically generate the numa
topology xml, using the libvirt config classes.

Change-Id: Ibdbce1c54003ae708b6c7f4b0874ca1ad96bfa07

commit_message:
Add a post_test_hook for gate-run functional tests

This does the necessary to gather up the results and publish them
properly for the gate job. Based on similar changes done for
python-novaclient.

Change-Id: Ib1f63aed9425fc8418fb9ddfe32f2d53f4b7c2b2

commit_message:
Add cli functional tests from tempest

test_readonly_ceilometer is migrated from
./tempest/cli/simple_read_only/telemetry

A new 'functional' target is available in tox. In order for these
tests to pass OS_PASSWORD, OS_AUTH_URL, OS_USERNAME
and OS_TENANT_NAME need to be set in the environment before running
the tests, e.g:

    source src/devstack/openrc demo demo && tox -efunctional

Subsequent patches will remove tests from tempest and add thes tests
to project-config for gate checks.

Change-Id: I3ce5ddbe471d70e8775ec5a1cc908a95a335b5e7

but assume only contain ascii characters, which will cause UnicodeEncodeError
when alarm's name or description has unicode characters.

The oslo-incubator.cliutils.print_dict() is more friendly to unicode,
but it has no sort option, and has different line wrap strategy. Since
the upstream improvement can be low progress, this patch adds unicode
support based on current code.

commit_message:
Support unicode for alarm

We're using ceilometer.common.utils.print_dict() for displaying alarm,
but assume only contain ascii characters, which will cause UnicodeEncodeError
when alarm's name or description has unicode characters.

The oslo-incubator.cliutils.print_dict() is more friendly to unicode,
but it has no sort option, and has different line wrap strategy. Since
the upstream improvement can be low progress, this patch adds unicode
support based on current code.

Change-Id: Ia58d5813c6f80cb8b44bf7636e1efc0cdd6e6d5b
Closes-Bug: #1412300
(cherry picked from commit f1f452405a80884c7a9cd78cad4aa4d73e290745)

After we port to oslo-incubator.apiclient, the project_id can no
longer be specified for alarm-{,threhsold,combination}-{create,update}
and sample-create, this is because client.AuthPlugin registers a CLI
argument named --os-project-id which will shadow the project-id
argument.

Since os-project-id is used for Keystone V3 API, we should not
remove it from AuthPlugin, so this patch moves the dest of project_id
to {alarm,sample}_project_id, and adds a decorator to restore shadowed

Change-Id: I0ce2416dccd61eb50584799e6df0b8c45d44cdda

commit_message:
Enable specified project_id in CLI commands

After we port to oslo-incubator.apiclient, the project_id can no
longer be specified for alarm-{,threhsold,combination}-{create,update}
and sample-create, this is because client.AuthPlugin registers a CLI
argument named --os-project-id which will shadow the project-id
argument.

Since os-project-id is used for Keystone V3 API, we should not
remove it from AuthPlugin, so this patch moves the dest of project_id
to {alarm,sample}_project_id, and adds a decorator to restore shadowed
project_id field when we call v2 client.

Change-Id: I0ce2416dccd61eb50584799e6df0b8c45d44cdda
Closes-Bug: #1393489
(cherry picked from commit 0c23c62cef6f1388d26c04d6cf0e74153db0a0b5)

commit_message:
Fixes bug with Client function not setting up SSL params

There are instances where some applications (heat, rally) instantiate
ceilometer client using Client function (instead of get_client) which
doesn't use the insecure and verify params properly. This fix will address
that.

Change-Id: I2f6346496e6ee36b5cd97ec6d9a732431532ff96
Closes-Bug: #1428370
(cherry picked from commit e7b8c48c60e85378e1e1d3c30bfb4cfa79f3105a)

[{'created': '2015-04-16 13:01:07.000000000', 'message': 'ceilometerclient fails with keystone v3 auth

When attempting to use keystone v3 Password authentication,
ceilometerclient is failing to pass the project information to
keystoneclient, which results in an unscoped token that lacks the
service catalog.

Change-Id: I980ba19f4b6b85ffc54d044184970c4902e62af4
Closes-Bug: #1438753
(cherry picked from commit d6ce587e95527c2c1aaeb2ce28afdcc64b32563f)
'}]
commit_message:
ceilometerclient fails with keystone v3 auth

When attempting to use keystone v3 Password authentication,
ceilometerclient is failing to pass the project information to
keystoneclient, which results in an unscoped token that lacks the
service catalog.

Change-Id: I980ba19f4b6b85ffc54d044184970c4902e62af4
Closes-Bug: #1438753
(cherry picked from commit d6ce587e95527c2c1aaeb2ce28afdcc64b32563f)

commit_message:
Set auth_plugin in __init__

This avoids auth_plugin being undefined when calling self.get_base_parser
without self.main having been called.

Closes-Bug: #1434264
Change-Id: Ic3a898ccecb865ff4e88d82538bcb04001d623db

commit_message:
Adds rsyslog-install.yml in to the gate scripts.

The rsyslog-install.yml play was not being run within run-playbooks.sh
script. The change makes it so that the AIO will now have the ability
to test the rsyslog server roles.

Change-Id: I30ea36ad4fb6696aeedf76351e18e09cf5e50a1e
Closes-Bug: 1446275

Fix value for default_archive_policy

While the string is parseable for oslo.config, it turns out to be really
badly rendered in the configuration file that is being auto-generated.

PyECLib is a requirement for Erasure Coding in Swift (a critical
new feature being introduced in Kilo).  In addition to fixing
several bugs, 1.0.7 eliminates the need for a few work-around code
in Swift.  This code was only to hide issues in the current version,

commit_message:
Bump PyECLib version from 1.0.3 to 1.0.7

PyECLib is a requirement for Erasure Coding in Swift (a critical
new feature being introduced in Kilo).  In addition to fixing
several bugs, 1.0.7 eliminates the need for a few work-around code
in Swift.  This code was only to hide issues in the current version,
but it also ends up breaking some third-party integration.  In order
to enable expected functionality and to avoid dealing with deprecation
issues right from the beginning, we hope to bump the minium PyECLib
requirement to 1.0.7.

Change-Id: I03e059e7335656c22be28ffd6157b56e13bdfc1b

commit_message:
Bump PyECLib version from 1.0.3 to 1.0.7

PyECLib is a requirement for Erasure Coding in Swift (a critical
new feature being introduced in Kilo).  In addition to fixing
several bugs, 1.0.7 eliminates the need for a few work-around code
in Swift.  This code was only to hide issues in the current version,
but it also ends up breaking some third-party integration.  In order
to enable expected functionality and to avoid dealing with deprecation
issues right from the beginning, we hope to bump the minium PyECLib
requirement to 1.0.7.

Change-Id: I03e059e7335656c22be28ffd6157b56e13bdfc1b

commit_message:
Clone external plugins before overriding defaults

This patch clones external plugin repositories before overriding
default configuration parameters.

Closes-Bug: 1441058
Change-Id: Ie14fcb897cb40b1604bfb5869baa0dec58e51bce

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-15 13:45:31.000000000', 'message': "fix lock concurrency issues with certain drivers

This change adds a test to ensure that lock acquired from different
threads/processes work as expected. And fixes drivers when they won't.

With file driver, when two threads acquire the lock, when the first one
releases it, the second get a 'ValueError: I/O operation on closed file'
because the first have closed the file after releasing the lock.
Now, the file is open when the lock object is created and we let the GC
to close it when we don't need it anymore

With mysql, postgres, kazoo driver, multiple acquire inside the same
backend session, doesn't work like a exclusive lock, so we track the
status locally when we get the lock inside a process.

Change-Id: Ic990a79c9baebe534409c1a433e21f4a2f9a7d6a
(cherry picked from commit 6bab678e6ea1a5b087a636279f2db873554a4116)
"}]
commit_message:
fix lock concurrency issues with certain drivers

This change adds a test to ensure that lock acquired from different
threads/processes work as expected. And fixes drivers when they won't.

With file driver, when two threads acquire the lock, when the first one
releases it, the second get a 'ValueError: I/O operation on closed file'
because the first have closed the file after releasing the lock.
Now, the file is open when the lock object is created and we let the GC
to close it when we don't need it anymore

With mysql, postgres, kazoo driver, multiple acquire inside the same
backend session, doesn't work like a exclusive lock, so we track the
status locally when we get the lock inside a process.

Change-Id: Ic990a79c9baebe534409c1a433e21f4a2f9a7d6a
(cherry picked from commit 6bab678e6ea1a5b087a636279f2db873554a4116)

commit_message:
Add retry to tgtadm create_target

There are issues where the --update call to tgtadm will fail
during target creation.  In Kilo we fixed this during the
refactoring by adding a retry decorator around the update cal.

This patch adds the same retry mechanism around that call to address
the issue.

Change-Id: I0cc5d76093794b69a6e6393972235f735d17e989
Closes-Bug: 1437421

subject: Add a generic retry decorator to cinder/utils

commit_message:
Add a generic retry decorator to cinder/utils

Retries are something that we use in a number of
places, and could probably use in a few more.  Rather
than continue writing custom retry code or silly loops
let's add a generic retry decorator class that can be
initialized and used as needed.

This patch leverages the retrying library that's already
in OpenStack Requirements and used in other places.  We
just add a wrapper around it for some logging and add
a bit of error handling incase somebody sets retries to 0

Normally this sort of change wouldn't be proposed for a
backport to stable, however there are a number valid bugs
that have been fixed in stable that utilize this retry
mechanism, so we're going to propose it so we can
leverage it in other bug fix backports.

Co-Authored-By: Josh Harlow <harlowja@yahoo-inc.com>

Conflicts:
	cinder/tests/test_utils.py
	cinder/utils.py

Change-Id: I629373d3c75be591ccde5608c8c85f2debd47447
(cherry picked from commit ca73ed8f79fa58ef1eb5ba0567a56c957bde6f95)

As we want to cut release and branches to maintain stable releases, we
need to give the permission to gnocchi-release to do so.

commit_message:
Add cleaning network docs

Ironic requires a cleaning network uuid in Kilo when using the default
config. This adds docs for how to configure the option and notes this
must be done when upgrading from Juno to Kilo.

Change-Id: Ia5cc118daefa7e3d966f1ff219ab024cb47d81f5

commit_message:
Fix RabbitMQ OCF stop/start actions

W/o this fix, rabbitMQ OCF may hang on the stop or start
as it ignores the stop/wait commands exit code. This is an
issue as it prevents rabbit node from joining the cluster.

The solution is to report generic failure, if corresponding
commands timed out:
* Fix stop_server_process() timeout command exit code check
* Fix try_to_start_rmq_app() timeout command exit code check

Closes-bug: #1446190

Change-Id: I8a0ccdde88cbb4c8545427f5bd6bdca6856a4687
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Fix handling of pci_requests in consume_from_instance.

Properly retrieve requests from pci_requests in consume_from_instance.
Without this the call to numa_fit_instance_to_host will fail because
it expects the request list.
And change the order in which apply_requests and numa_fit_instance_to_host
are called. Calling apply_requests first will remove devices from pools
and  may make numa_fit_instance_to_host fail.

Change-Id: I41cf4e8e5c1dea5f91e5261a8f5e88f46c7994ef
Closes-bug: #1444021

commit_message:
Revert neutron with admin role

Looks neutron still require admin to work. With neutron policy,
the port binding for VM require admin permission.
https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/etc/policy.json#L53

A bug is opened against neutron.
https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1445475

Until it is changed by neutron, cookbook need to revert it back to
using admin role.

Related-Bug: #1436050

Change-Id: I8342f7da783c2fc7bb42488b6d461851f66b2228

commit_message:
Puppet OpenStack: enable Puppet 4.0 as non voting

Puppet 4.0 is out [1] so we want to support this release for our
modules.
* Create gate-puppet-{module}-puppet-unit-4.0 jobs for all Puppet
  OpenStack modules
* Enable the job in check as non-voting jobs

[1] https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppet/releases/tag/4.0.0

Change-Id: I9646bcd6f1d5f87753b9c862e029a563a4fd8da1

commit_message:
Improve title adding in 'Application Catalog' page

* App description (huge amout of text) is not shown as tooltip anymore;
* App title is shown in case overflow happened.
* Readme is fixed
* 'Application' is removed from form title, since it makes form description huge

Change-Id: I1923eb9eeeb5e2876c5f94fb8be86af859eb968f

commit_message:
Install Oozie UI on MapR clusters

It's needed to rebuild Oozie war with ExtJS archive
specified to make Oozie UI work. Note that we have
to rebuild it every time configure.sh runs on Oozie
node because script rebuilds it w/o ExtJS.

Closes-Bug: #1439452
Change-Id: I14e2c6742913898f3a129d4423c8cbf2be8f7632

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 7711, 'date': '2015-04-15 12:05:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 13997, 'date': '2015-04-15 12:59:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-04-15 14:21:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Honesty, I don't actually like the change. I liked how they were aligned originally :-("}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-04-15 14:22:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I'm fine if people want this change. I just want to register that I don't like the new look."}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-04-15 15:20:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think the point of E129 is so that the conditional statement is not aligned with the action block.

 if (some_cond and
     another_cond):
     action_block

instead:

 if (some_cond and
         another_cond):
     action_block'}, {'account_id': 14619, 'date': '2015-04-15 18:43:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-04-16 13:42:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-04-17 17:43:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 14923, 'date': '2015-04-19 22:38:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-04-20 10:19:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Hi John,

Nothing wrong with the change itself, and it already has 3 +2 so one can go and approve it. But I'd like to point out that E129 is optional as defined in the pep8 style guide[1].

I like the flexibility, as stated in pep8[1], the multiple line "if conditional", with our without that extra space is acceptable. So my vote here is for the flexibility, I think we should support both ways.

And as Ruby, I also like it more without the extra space.

[1] https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#indentation'}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-04-20 16:14:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Okay, so we can let people do it either way.  In reality I think most of the code is already compliant with E129 as there were a limited number of changes made.

Leave it as is and allow code like this:

     if (some_cond1 and
         another_cond and
         another_cond2):
         if (some_cond2 and
             another_cond1):
             action_block'}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-04-20 16:16:55.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Since E129 is optional and don't have a strong consensus.  Abandon this change."}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-04-20 16:19:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi, Would it make sense to add a comment to tox.ini as to why we're not fixing E129. To avoid going through this discussion again, or at least if we do, we have these comments as a starting point :-)"}]

commit_message:
Refactor code in nova-setup recipe

    Refactored two sections of nova network setup.
        - clarified variable names in array (Lines 51-54)
        - rewrote logic around bridge_interface and
          bridge_dev parameter creation (Lines 57 - 60)

    The bug mentions lines 47-71, but lines 61-71
    seem to be ok.
Change-Id: If00994ccacad8de96c6f55fb3231985f98587f12
Closes-Bug: #1412604

Applying copy_update to all policy.json files

Adding support for dynamically updating the policy files for
nova, glance, neutron, cinder and heat. Uses the copy_update
plugin to detect any updates and applies the changes to the default
policy.json

Implements: blueprint dynamically-manage-policy.json
Change-Id: I573229d6f18a5fe32460b2373ab8b2c36ac722b4
(cherry picked from commit e7931323aa878564426d8999b97ad56f59c47222)

commit_message:
Increment max FormatVersion

max_format_version is now 2.1.0
use semantic_version (found in global_requirements) for comparisons
added IncorrectFormat exception, to help distinguish format errors from
any other AgentExceptions

Closes Bug: #1441276

Co-Authored-By: Kirill Zaitsev <kzaitsev@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Start switching to declarative package-installs

Make use of the package-installs element to declare in yaml format the
packages to be installed at the beginning of a phase.

Other than reducing the amont of explicit 'install-packages pkg1 ...'
invocations, they can also be installed just once per-phase.

Change-Id: I1f1acfb2bd74fed5cf4c0b48bc739f7f75c35d83

commit_message:
Make sure the RPC use str's

Decimal objects are not serialized properly, so convert them to str to
make sure that RPC calls work.

Change-Id: I2c938d866b6c50acaee2989c330a5fd6c7062f77

We don't need all attributes from RoleAssignment model for
_get_metadata() method, so we can select only required fields from
database. This will reduce DB usage an speed-up this query.

Change-Id: I1ada088717cf826bbb84651486cd186c34567743
"}]
commit_message:
Minor tune DB query in Assignment._get_metadata()

We don't need all attributes from RoleAssignment model for
_get_metadata() method, so we can select only required fields from
database. This will reduce DB usage an speed-up this query.

Enable access to HAProxy stats page

Enable access to the HAProxy stats page. The listen directive is bound
to the controller virtual IP address.

Add $::galera_bootstrapped fact

This fact let puppet know if the node is part of a Galera cluster
already or not.

commit_message:
Fix the public access on /

The keystone middleware patch removed the public access on /, which
currently breaks the devstack deployment.

This is a quick fix before https://review.openstack.org/#/c/123408/ gets
merged.

Change-Id: I31ffcd0b2d1f4fc38840bffe3bceb0f65c22b30d

commit_message:
Fix resources rendering in web browsers

Since indexer return object rather than dict, jinja templates was
unable to use python dicts API to extract informations.

This commit also remove flask dependency.

Change-Id: I3ec8e6519b03b46f60b2e95cf6658c762c6a6583

commit_message:
Allow force-delete irrespective of VM task_state

Cannot delete vm instance if duplicate delete requests are sent.

When user sends request to delete an instance, its task_state gets
changed to 'deleting' state. When an instance task_state is already in
'deleting' state and if at that moment the rabbitmq-server get crashed
by some reasons, then the instance task_state remains in 'deleting'
state and user won't be able to delete the instance forever.

At this moment, there is only one way to delete the instances, whose
task_state is in 'deleting' state, by restarting the nova-compute
services where these instances are running.

To avoid restarting the nova-compute service manually, modified the
force-delete api to allow instance deletion irrespective of
instance task_state.

Added new module to use delete_types as constants and replaced all
delete_type string occurances with new constants.

Note: This patch is not 1:1 cherry-pick, I have revoked rpc changes
to make it work with nodes running a mixture of old and new code.

Closes-Bug: #1308342

Change-Id: I4d0e47662a80109ef9622d85455587d487e47c01
(cherry picked from commit 222d44532c65ddf3f26532ced217890628352536)

commit_message:
Do not make RabbitMQ listen on public vip

Currently RabbitMQ is listening on both private vip and public vip.
There is no need for RabbitMQ to listen on the public vip, so we remove
it.

Change-Id: I82ea2e1e18b7710ae391ffe4903439a9330b1461

commit_message:
Added support for rating module priority

Rating modules are now sorted based on a priority number. The modules
with the highest priority are loaded first.
Added API calls to set the priority of a module.

Change-Id: I84d9f6c31014c3164e5b7d8efdd3c909e342df96

commit_message:
Replace 'metrics' with 'meters' in option

So that the openstack manuals are consistent and use the
same (right) term, this replaces the term 'metrics' with
'meters' in the help for the config option
send_sensor_data_interval.

DocImpact

Closes-bug: #1436371

Change-Id: Id88058bf2fe070a8e0774857f2c5690a60c30de0

commit_message:
Refactor and Fix Translation Code for PER and DER Formats

For private keys, both in PEM and DER format, we will use
PKCS#8.  This patch corrects our DER format so it is now PKCS#8.
Also, move the secret type logic into translation methods and
complete the unit tests.

Closes-Bug: #1445575
Change-Id: Ifacbc496e1120b5593345ca0d90a5fa2fadb3465

commit_message:
enable events in ceilometer

events were included in ceilometer as of Juno, while adding tempest
tests to verify events, we should also test against Juno as well.

commit_message:
Hide unpublic and not owned packages

* applies to 'App Catalog' page
* applies to 'Environment Components' page
* show user-plus icon on "Package Definitions" panel

Since admin user are allowed to manage not owned packages,
all apps were shown in App Catalog page, while it should not.

Change-Id: I97a6875b50ad4863b746e6be79a46e1e1fecf7f8
Closes-Bug: #1444098

commit_message:
Update share driver parameters

Updating share driver parameters to support upstream changes:
 - New NetApp driver options (single and multi-SVM)
 - Share servers in both NetApp and generic drivers

Change-Id: I1d4b4a9e82a7fa187b87a761a07bb5bf75f23951

commit_message:
Support network plugin model

Supports configuration parameters for the following new network
plugins:
 - Neutron (formerly the only option)
 - Neutron single network
 - Nova networking
 - Standalone network

Documentation for these plugins is in review here:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171166/

Change-Id: Ida57ae5551c962791eaddacb695996cf4e8dec23

tarballs.o.o/sahara

commit_message:
[devstack] Automatically enable required service in devstack

* Disable nova-networking
* Enable neutron
* Enable heat

Closes-Bug: #1439620

commit_message:
Revert "Add elevator parameter to startup kernel options, and set it to deadline."

This reverts commit cf3d193fad5eee3ff345379ced42ad7be8e4b6b2.

As shown by simple benchmark on Launchpad report[1], the change has decreased the performance.

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/fuel/+bug/1418126/comments/14

Change-Id: Id5cef7adbfcd6da20d71ccb6f2cdc6209c637919

commit_message:
[DO-NOT-MERGE] Enable libvirt debug logs

Along with enabling debug logs, add this libvirt filter to monitor QMP
commands -- 1:qemu_monitor

This is to troubleshoot a libvirt error seen in the CI gate (on
CentOS7):

  "Caught Segmentation violation dumping internal log buffer"

With versions:

  libvirt-1.1.1-29.el7_0.7.x86_64
  qemu-system-x86-2.0.0-1.el7.3.x86_64

Change-Id: Ia92214725048e0fc2446132da87c99ca6c0226bd

commit_message:
Add validators to k8s pod UI

Kubernetes imposes a number of restrictions for the names
of pods and labels syntax.
This patch adds validation of pod name and labels fields.

Change-Id: If93d1cc8750f1550aaa9649fdc012c302560b88d
Closes-Bug: #1445149

commit_message:
Add bay status check when rc create.

Now when we create rc,we didn't check the bay status
it require.It may cause some strange error.

Change-Id: I9bd043782be8c7370a118d3e059bbe9c078150cf
Closes-bug:#1445410

commit_message:
Add bay status check when service create.

Now when we create service, we didn't check the bay status
it require.It may cause some strange error.

Change-Id: Id5d59ea3bee5ef1e63d9c8def1fd33e751b7dbe4
Closes-bug:#1445406

commit_message:
Pin puppetlabs-concat to 1.2.1 in fixtures

Puppet Labs is in the process of releasing a 2.0.0 version of
puppetlabs-concat, which will have many breaking changes that affect
many dependent modules. Changes have been merged to master, but not yet
released. While we figure out what changes we need to make in our own
modules and wait for updates in dependent modules, we should just pin
to a stable version.

Change-Id: I618cb53dd8e8ba4e7ef240ac1ef19c35ec56948a

[{'created': '2015-04-18 17:31:37.000000000', 'message': 'Add logging config to cinder.conf

Part of the effort to clean up the Cinder logs is to use
the resource tag in the log format.  We also want to have
some consistency with other projects in how we do logging.

This change adds the logging format to cinder.conf similar to
what Nova and others use, and most importantly turns on the use
of the resource tag that's in olso_log.

We're slowly cleaning up the logging in Cinder by doing things
like replacing "Delete volume %(volume_id)s compoleted" with
("Delete volume completed successfully.", resource=volume)

It woudl be good to have these picked up as we transition so we're
not missing info.  Also, there's sure to be cases where "volume"
isn't a valid dbref and we find issues that need fixed.

commit_message:
Add logging config to cinder.conf

Part of the effort to clean up the Cinder logs is to use
the resource tag in the log format.  We also want to have
some consistency with other projects in how we do logging.

This change adds the logging format to cinder.conf similar to
what Nova and others use, and most importantly turns on the use
of the resource tag that's in olso_log.

We're slowly cleaning up the logging in Cinder by doing things
like replacing "Delete volume %(volume_id)s compoleted" with
("Delete volume completed successfully.", resource=volume)

It woudl be good to have these picked up as we transition so we're
not missing info.  Also, there's sure to be cases where "volume"
isn't a valid dbref and we find issues that need fixed.

Change-Id: I193637fea14d97183f6a9782f37d8edcf929e0c4

commit_message:
Adding .to_wrapped_dict to node_group_template update

The node group template update operation now
wraps its output with to_wrapped_dict to yield json
that accurately reflects the node group template object.

Change-Id: I19d538c9842d1bfaa9dc35c30941a06d86af0cc3
Closes-Bug: #1445559

commit_message:
use message id to generate hbase unique key

We currently can disable computing signature for metering message,
but HBase still uses signature as a dimension to generate unique row
key, this will lead to different samples treated as same one.

Message id should be used in stead of message signature, because
id will always exist and also unique.

Change-Id: I47cdce59c9934573076cf609ce1a0c37aea75c44
Closes-Bug: #1445227

commit_message:
Catalog Index Service - glance devstack

Implements: blueprint catalog-index-service

The changes to lib/glance incorporate the new g-search service.
The g-search service is optional.
To enable it add the following line to devstack/local.conf:
enable_service g-search

In addition to deploying g-search, the changes will also populate a
search type of keystone service and adds in appropriate endpoints.

Change-Id: I0272d56bc2e50e8174db78bd449f65f60f7f4000

maybe we just add exclude=ruby* (or ruby2.1) to yum.conf ? if we lock version, we  cant update old ruby packages'}, {'account_id': 7195, 'date': '2015-03-10 18:05:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Roman, your idea blocks ALL ruby packages. My solution only locks core ruby packages. You can't set any hardcoded options like "ruby<2.0".'}, {'account_id': 8787, 'date': '2015-03-10 18:40:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Matt, one of the options Roman proposed was to have a more narrow exclude=ruby-2.1* in yum.conf, how is that worse than versionlock? I can see three benefits: 1) it's only locking ruby interpreter itself; 2) it uses the same mechanism you use to install the ruby packages initially; 3) it doesn't add a dependency on a yum plugin.

Still, I dislike both approaches due to their impact on our ability to patch ruby related packages on target nodes, I'll comment about that on the bug."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-20 13:32:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

commit_message:
Pin ruby CentOS to 1.8.7

Adds yum-plugin-versionlock package to installation
and locks ruby packages to 1.8.7.

Change-Id: Id5dcea6fd80e66f391d642a0c0b659de32425ea4
Closes-Bug: #1403088

commit_message:
DO NOT MERGE: Move shared code to a common place to avoid duplication.

NOTE: This is just a suggestion change for what is being done in gerrit
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/175206/  . i.e. this gerrit will be
potentially folded into 175206 and then abandoned.

Added _generate_router_dict() to create router dictionary used by
both add_router_interface and remove_router_interface.

Change-Id: Ia7a47dbf435c20960323bb38437036121489212e

commit_message:
Fix ranges in the plugins deployment order spec

This commit brings ranges for Fuel plugins
into the desired order, so that 5000 would
go right after 4999 (not after 6999).

Change-Id: I9e9fea36b74720761e9b5dacf81102d16f91ada7
Closes-Bug: 1444942

commit_message:
Updated Protocol named constants

The L3 protocol name constants should be removed from
neutron/plugins/common/constants.py because for instance, there
exists a constant already in neutron/common/constants.py for
tcp - PROTO_NAME_TCP.

Moved out FWaaS specific constants from
neutron.plugins.common.constants to here.

Reference:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/166879/

(cherry picked from commit d6559ddcd0befc9434f4d27ee0bb7e31cf98c60e)
Change-Id: Ic9dc026f4165c3ea00d472bfb7bd8edaf89ce7c0

Moreover, I think you should have unmounted the cdrom drive, prior to ejecting it and avoid the I/O errors.
I'm pretty sure the same behaviour you would see with any other bus (ide, etc..)"}, {'account_id': 11298, 'date': '2015-04-15 14:57:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

That's one way to prevent the error. 
Shouldn't it be our goal to make sure that no error occurs to the user instead of making sure no error occurs if the user does everything he's supposed to do?"}, {'account_id': 8802, 'date': '2015-04-15 15:22:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm not sure what are you suggesting..?
The error that you have seen comes from the guest OS kernel.

I doubt that we can force the guest OS to unmount the device, not from QEMU nor Libvirt, especially not from nova..

In this patch you are suggesting to using virtio-blk as a default bus for a CDROM, however, that will not change the guest OS behaviour.

Moreover, if that for some reason works for you, there is still no reason to that from the code.
As I've pointed out in the review and your bug, you can just add a glace property to your image."}, {'account_id': 11298, 'date': '2015-04-15 15:31:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I saw your suggestion with the attribute a second after writing. Sorry. I already tested the approach with the attribute and I think it's a good solution. Thank you."}, {'account_id': 8802, 'date': '2015-04-15 15:51:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

No problem. Does that work differently on system-z with virtio-blk? 
Are you able to eject the disk without unmounting it?
If yes, then maybe we should proceed with your patch.
I assumed that this should have the same behaviour.'}, {'account_id': 11298, 'date': '2015-04-16 06:32:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

virtio-blk doesn't allow eject on system-z. It would be a step back to be on the save side. I personally like your proposal better. virtio-scsi should be the long-term goal. Tomorrow is a discussion with the team. After that I'm going to abandon the change."}, {'account_id': 11298, 'date': '2015-04-20 13:40:40.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Change config drive attachement from virtio-scsi to virtio-blk.

Interim Workaround to prevent problems caused by virtio-scsi.
Should be changed back, when virtio-scsi is fixed in KVM.

Change-Id: I5d76b6f11f07d299307fcb50f62de71e0d61e599
Closes-Bug: 1443501

refactor ping_check

Encapsulate all the neutron specific things you have to do ping a
neutron guest into a separate script. Refactor the main ping_check so
all logic is contained within it.

I know this is a workaround to a bug in the recent version of keepalived. I wonder this workaround needs to be applied to all env or environments with the specific version of keepalived. In envs with the specific version of keepalives, non-preempt mode does not work according to the commit message, so it also sounds reasonable that non-preempt is disabled if keepavlied is the recent version with a bug.'}, {'account_id': 6502, 'date': '2015-03-23 09:28:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2015-03-23 18:58:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

@Akihiro: Changing between pre-emption and non-preemption is pretty significant to how L3 HA works, so I'd like it at least consistent and not dependent on keepalived version. That being said, after talking with various people:

* Ubuntu is using an archaic version of keepalived and is not affected.
* Debian is using 1.2.13, which is just before the regression of 1.2.14, so is not affected
* Fedora 20, 21 and 22 were using 1.2.15 and Ryan O'Hara was kind enough to package a version with a fix/revert that went in to keepalived
* CentOS and RHEL 7 were using 1.2.13 like Debian, so were not affected.
* I don't know about SUSE or any other distro I might have missed in my wonderful passage across space and time.

To summarize, I'm parking this change for now."}, {'account_id': 2874, 'date': '2015-03-24 08:03:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

how about making the pre-empt an option item?'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-03-24 15:27:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

I agree that non-preempt and preempt modes are very different. Hopefully every distributions release the fixed version.
I am not confident we change the behavior of L3-HA at this stage of the release.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-25 23:19:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

commit_message:
Enable pre-emption for L3 HA

Enable pre-emption to work a around a new-ish keepalived bug.
Pre-emption means that if a master node dies and a backup takes over,
then when the old master comes back up it will re-assume (Or pre-empt)
the role of master. This means more failovers, but better distribution
of master states.

Closes-Bug: #1433172
Change-Id: Ib06b3b998f0ec673cfed7f05959b0cfb9c5b927d

commit_message:
Install 'yum-plugin-priorities' on all slaves

Since Fuel 6.1 we are able to work with custom set of repos with custom
priorities. By default, yum is unable to work with them, but it could be
fixed by installing 'yum-plugin-priorities'.

Change-Id: I3f5a95abcae18dbca5b3c39b0949a8c46cb7ef69
Related-Bug: #1440074

commit_message:
Install 'yum-plugin-priorities' on master node

Since we can deal with several repos at once, it's a good idea to add
possibility to set different priorities for them.

Change-Id: I0942bdc3233c5bf4f5aff60599fcaa78cc00cc63
Related-Bug: #1440074

[{'created': '2015-04-17 15:38:15.000000000', 'message': "New manifest file to deploy Cisco N1KV-VEM

Background on 'N1KV-VEM’: It is the host-side component of N1KV
implementing the notion of Virtual Ports for VM Interfaces and also
handling the VM data-traffic. VEM is implemented as a couple of
user-space processes and also has a KLM for efficient data-path
switching.

VEM manifests does: setting up the Config-File for VEM service,
Starting VEM service and finally adding physical ports (along with
port-profile) to the VEM

Change-Id: Ibc8f1c4d2d743589e452ae6d1d87b5bfa123bc3a
(cherry picked from commit 48aa3fbbe294eeef88e455a219dddc70334b9990)
"}]
commit_message:
New manifest file to deploy Cisco N1KV-VEM

Background on 'N1KV-VEM’: It is the host-side component of N1KV
implementing the notion of Virtual Ports for VM Interfaces and also
handling the VM data-traffic. VEM is implemented as a couple of
user-space processes and also has a KLM for efficient data-path
switching.

VEM manifests does: setting up the Config-File for VEM service,
Starting VEM service and finally adding physical ports (along with
port-profile) to the VEM

Change-Id: Ibc8f1c4d2d743589e452ae6d1d87b5bfa123bc3a
(cherry picked from commit 48aa3fbbe294eeef88e455a219dddc70334b9990)

commit_message:
DO NOT MERGE: Example of new getter

This adds a private method that our get_THING() API methods can
call to give them more functionality (filtering, getting all matches,
erroring on non-unique matches) while still maintaining backwards
compatibility, which is to get one thing even if there are multiple
matches.

Change-Id: I46cac7c195019b4a6a0dfb547611516dcedaf8b1

commit_message:
RST Guides: Fix Report a bug link

We need to have html_show_sourcelink as True (default) so that "Report a
bug" works, otherwise the source name is not available.

Change-Id: I5300fa02908757ed77b30ef4bb9894136318e364

Fix for AttributeError admin_remote when calling is_ntpd_active()

commit_message:
removed asterisk for admin state in network create

In network create and update, the admin_state parameter is optional
but in horizon forms, asterisk is shown for admin state choice field which is wrong.

In this patch, asterisk mark is removed for admin state choice field in network create and update forms.

Change-Id: I349915f8fbe496cf79d33cd54e9c405799eb61e2
Closes-Bug: #1441511

Also it is possible to change the settings on the fly (e.g. during adding new nodes to the cluster, or other maintenance) I don't think it is worth taking into account how it complicates things (how to detect when the setting can be return back, how to monitor easily what settings are currently applied).

These settings are commonly recommended (as static configuration), see e.g.

http://www.slideshare.net/Inktank_Ceph/scaling-ceph-at-cern

commit_message:
Decrease I/O load when adding/removing OSD nodes

* Set options osd_max_backfills and osd_recovery_max_active
* Fix the options which use white space instead of underscore

Closes-bug: #1430845
Related-bug: #1374969
Change-Id: I3cdcec6c5bd39e5cbc55ecf8a29b751c784851a0

commit_message:
run dstat with run_process

It is not clear to me why this can't use run_process?  Currently we
end up with two log-files both with the same thing

- dstat.txt.gz which comes from the "tee" and is symlinked into
  SCREEN_LOGDIR, so gets picked-up by the gate scripts
- screen-dstat.txt.gz which comes from screen_it

Change-Id: I00b9e09b8d44f72ff14e69dc6e4a4bd5e2a0439e

commit_message:
Parse objects related datetimes using timeutils.parse_isotime() in db api

Before a TaskLog object can replace the conductor methods used today, an
issue in how object related datetimes are handled in the db api needs to
be fixed.

Currently, serialized datetimes are converted back into proper datetimes
using timeutils.parse_strtime() when instead timeutils.parse_isotime()
should really be used.

Related to blueprint liberty-objects

Change-Id: I26027934b3ae54db455c43950031a224bba65b43
